## PHASED DELIVERY

Each phase = a shippable wedge. After each phase: lint, tests, smoke, KB review-request for Codex.

### Phase 1 — Schema foundations (migration 035)
- Migration 035 adds `projects.org_id` (nullable String FK to organizations.id, ON DELETE SET NULL).
- Migration 035 adds `users.default_org_id` (nullable String FK to organizations.id, ON DELETE SET NULL).
- New table `project_transfers`:
  ```
  id String PK
  project_id String? FK projects(id) ON DELETE SET NULL  -- nullable for audit durability
  project_git_remote_snapshot String?                    -- STABLE identity (git_remote is unique)
  project_name_snapshot String?                          -- human-readable label only
  initiated_by String FK users(id)
  target_user_id String? FK users(id) ON DELETE SET NULL  -- pending recipient
  from_scope String  -- "personal" or org_id
  to_scope String    -- "personal" or org_id
  state String       -- "pending" / "accepted" / "rejected" / "cancelled"
  accepted_by String? FK users(id)
  created_at, accepted_at, updated_at
  ```
  Durability invariants (CEO directive, KB 230 #1; refined across
  Codex Phase-1 rounds 2-4, KB entries 233/235/238):
  - `project_id` ON DELETE SET NULL — a hard project delete clears the live
    linkage but the audit row survives. Identity is preserved via the
    `project_git_remote_snapshot` column (the STABLE durable identifier —
    `projects.git_remote_normalized` is `unique=True`, so two deleted
    projects with the same display name remain distinguishable in audit
    history). `project_name_snapshot` is a display-only label, not
    load-bearing for identity. Both columns are populated by the Phase 2
    route at create time.
  - `from_scope` / `to_scope` are plain TEXT (not FK) so they survive an org
    deletion intact.
  - `accepted_by` FK has NO ondelete clause — post-accept user deletion is
    rejected by the FK (the auditor's identity stays attached).
  - `target_user_id` ON DELETE SET NULL — pending recipient deletion clears
    the field; Phase 2 route treats target_user_id=NULL on a pending row as
    "stale, auto-cancel".

  `target_user_id` is the inbox-recipient column (set on initiate, distinct
  from `accepted_by` which only fills on accept). For auto-accept shapes
  (initiator == target — e.g. a user transferring their own personal project
  to an org they belong to), the Phase 2 route sets target_user_id =
  initiated_by AND flips state to `accepted` at create time.
- Model classes updated (`Project.org_id`, `User.default_org_id`, new `ProjectTransfer`).
- Backfill: existing projects get `org_id = NULL` (personal). No data migration risk.
- Tests: 9 (defaults nullable, org_id set roundtrip, FK ondelete=SET NULL on projects.org_id + users.default_org_id via schema inspection, ProjectTransfer roundtrip + inbox composite index `(state, target_user_id)`, audit-durability FK metadata canary for project_id=SET NULL, both-snapshots roundtrip, end-to-end audit-survives-project-delete with stable identity, migration module chain canary).

DONE when: migration 035 applies cleanly on a fresh PG + on an upgrade from migration 034 with real session data, all 9 tests pass, ruff clean. (PG-flavored migration runtime test is deferred to Forge as a v0.10.x DevOps task — KB entry 237.)

### Phase 2 — Project transfer endpoints
- `POST /api/v1/projects/{id}/transfer` — initiate. Body: `{to: "personal" | <org_id>}`. Owner-or-org-admin gate. Creates a `project_transfers` row in `pending` state. Sends a notification (email + dashboard) to the target user. Returns `transfer_id`.
- `POST /api/v1/transfers/{transfer_id}/accept` — target user only. Flips `state` to `accepted`, atomically updates `projects.org_id` (or sets to NULL for transfer-out), writes the accepted_at timestamp.
- `POST /api/v1/transfers/{transfer_id}/reject` — target user only.
- `POST /api/v1/transfers/{transfer_id}/cancel` — initiator only, while pending.
- `GET /api/v1/transfers?state=pending&direction=incoming|outgoing` — list (for dashboard inbox).
- Audit log row written on every state transition.
- Tests: 10 (every state transition × happy-path + edge cases: stale pending cancel after accept, rejecting a non-existent transfer, non-target trying to accept, etc.)

DONE when: every transfer state transition covered, server tests pass, REST contract documented in `docs/cli-reference.md` or new `docs/transfers.md`.

